  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And be thou instructed, O Jerusalem,.... Or \"corrected\" (s); receive discipline or instructions by chastisements and corrections, return by repentance, that the evils threatened may not come: this shows the affection of the Lord to his people, notwithstanding all their sins; that their amendment, and not their destruction, were pleasing to him; that it was with reluctance he was about to visit them in the manner threatened; and that even now it was not too late, provided they were instructed and reformed; but, if not, they must expect what follows: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "lest my soul depart from thee; his Shechinah, or divine Presence, and all the tokens of his love, favour, and good will. The Targum interprets it of the Word of the Lord, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "\"lest my Word cast thee off;'' ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "see Romans 11:1, or, \"lest my soul pluck itself from thee\"; or \"be plucked\" (t), and separated from thee: the phrase denotes an utter separation, a forcible one, joined with the utmost abhorrence and detestation. In Ezekiel 23:18, it is rendered, \"my mind was alienated\"; it denotes disunion and disaffection. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Romans 11:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", or, \"lest my soul pluck itself from thee\"; or \"be plucked\" (t), and separated from thee: the phrase denotes an utter separation, a forcible one, joined with the utmost abhorrence and detestation. In ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Ezekiel 23:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", it is rendered, \"my mind was alienated\"; it denotes disunion and disaffection. ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lest I make thee desolate, a land not inhabited; the Targum adds, by way of illustration, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "\"as the land of Sodom;'' ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "so that not a man should dwell in it; see Jeremiah 4:25. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "so that not a man should dwell in it; see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jeremiah 4:25",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(s) \"cape disciplinam\", Vatablus; \"admitte disciplinam\", Cocceius; \"castigationem\", Schmidt. (t)    \"ut non luxetur, vel avellatur anima mea a te\", Vatablus, Junius & Tremellius, Schmidt. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(s) \"cape disciplinam\", Vatablus; \"admitte disciplinam\", Cocceius; \"castigationem\", Schmidt. (t)    \"ut non luxetur, vel avellatur anima mea a te\", Vatablus, Junius & Tremellius, Schmidt. ",
            "children": []
